    <div class="hidden">
        <div id="a2_1">
            <ul>
                <li><b>Purpose</b>: container for all other events. Sprints are the heartbeat of Scrum,
                    where ideas are turned into value.</li>
                <li><b>Duration</b>: fixed length events of one month or less</li>
                <li>No changes are made that would endanger the Sprint Goal</li>
                <li>Quality does not decrease</li>
                <li>Product Backlog is refined as needed</li>
                <li>Scope may be clarified and renegotiated with the Product Owner as more is learned</li>
                <li>Enables predictability by ensuring inspection and adaptation of progress toward a Product Goal</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a2_2">
            <ul>
                <li><b>Purpose</b>: initiates the Sprint by laying out the work to be performed for the Sprint</li>
                <li><b>Duration</b>: maximum of eight hours for a one-month Sprint</li>
                <li>Resulting plan is created by the collaborative work of the entire Scrum Team</li>
                <li>Product Owner ensures that attendees are prepared to discuss the most important Product Backlog
                    items and how they map to the Product Goal</li>
                <li>Scrum Team may also invite other people to attend Sprint Planning to provide advice. </li>
            </ul>
            <br/>
            <b>Topics</b>
            <ul>
                <li>Why is this Sprint valuable?
                    <ul>
                        <li>Scrum Team then collaborates to define a Sprint Goal</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>What can be Done this Sprint?
                    <ul>
                        <li>Select items from the Product Backlog to include in the current Sprint (Spring Backlog)</li>
                        <li>Refine these items during this process, which increases understanding and confidence</li>
                        <li>Select how much can be completed within a Sprint (using capacity knowledge)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>How will the chosen work get done?
                    <ul>
                        <li>Plan the work necessary to create an Increment that meets the Definition of Done</li>
                        <li>Decompose Product Backlog items into smaller work items of one day or less</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a2_3">
            <ul>
                <li><b>Purpose</b>: inspect progress towards the Spring Goal</li>
                <li><b>Duration</b>: 15-minute</li>
                <li>Only for developers</li>
                <li>Adapt the Spring Backlog as necessary, adjusting the upcoming planned work</li>
                <li>Produces an actionable plan for the next day of work</li>
                <li>Improve communications, identify impediments, promote quick decision-making,
                    and consequently eliminate the need for other meetings.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a2_4">
            <ul>
                <li><b>Purpose</b>: inspect the outcome of the Sprint and determine future adaptations</li>
                <li><b>Duration</b>: maximum of four hours for a one-month Sprint</li>
                <li>Scrum Team presents the results of their work to key stakeholders and progress toward the
                    Product Goal is discussed</li>
                <li>Attendees collaborate on what to do next</li>
                <li>Product Backlog may also be adjusted to meet new opportunities</li>
                <li>Sprint Review is a working session and the Scrum Team should avoid limiting it to a presentation.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a2_5">
            <ul>
                <li><b>Purpose</b>: plan ways to increase quality and effectiveness</li>
                <li><b>Duration</b>: maximum of three hours for a one-month Sprint.</li>
                <li>Scrum Team inspects how the last Sprint went with regards to individuals, interactions, processes,
                    tools, and their Definition of Done</li>
                <li>Scrum Team discusses what went well during the Sprint, what problems it encountered, and how those
                    problems were (or were not) solved.</li>
                <li>The Scrum Team identifies the most helpful changes to improve its effectiveness. The most impactful
                    improvements are addressed as soon as possible. They may even be added to the Sprint Backlog for
                    the next Sprint.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

