    <div class="hidden">
        <div id="a5_1">
            <ul>
                <li>Committed to create any aspect of usable increment each Sprint</li>
                <li>Creating plan for the Sprint – Sprint Backlog</li>
                <li>Following Definition of Done</li>
                <li>Adapting plan every day towards the Sprint Goal</li>
                <li>Holding each other accountable as professionals</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a5_2">
            <ul>
                <li>Single person, not a committee</li>
                <li>Maximized the value of the product resulting from the work of Scrum Team</li>
                <li>Accountable for effective Product Backlog management. If any change required in
                    Product Backlog – Product Owner needs to be convinced</li>
                <li>Develops and communicates Product Goal</li>
                <li>Creates and clearly communicate Product Backlog</li>
                <li>Orders Product Backlog</li>
                <li>Ensures that the Product Backlog is transparent, visible and understood</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a5_3">
            <ul>
                <li>Establishes Scrum</li>
                <li>Helps everyone to understand Scrum theory and practice. Coaches the team members.</li>
                <li>Accountable for Scrum Team effectiveness and improving practices</li>
            </ul>
            <br/>
            <b>Leader that serves to</b>
            <ul>
                <li>Scrum Team
                    <ul>
                        <li>Helps the Scrum Team to focus on creating high-value increments</li>
                        <li>Causing the removal of impediments during work</li>
                        <li>Ensuring that all Scrum events take place and are positive, productive,
                            and kept within the timebox.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Product Owner
                    <ul>
                        <li>Helps find techniques for effective Product Goal detection and Product Backlog management</li>
                        <li>Helps the Scrum Team to understand the need for clear and concise Product Backlog items</li>
                        <li>Helps to establish empirical product planning</li>
                        <li>Facilitates stakeholder collaboration</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Organization
                    <ul>
                        <li>Leading, training and coaching the organization in its Scrum adoption</li>
                        <li>Planning and advising Scrum implementations</li>
                        <li>Helping employees and stakeholders understand and apply empirical approach for complex work</li>
                        <li>Removing barriers between stakeholders and Scrum Team</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="hidden">
        <div id="a6_1">
            <ul>
                <li>Has a commitment to <b>Product Goal</b></li>
                <li>Emergent, ordered list of what is needed to improve the product</li>
                <li>Single source of work undertaken by the Scrum Team</li>
                <li>Items that can be Done by the Scrum Team within one Sprint are deemed ready for selection in a
                    Sprint Planning</li>
                <li>Items becomes “ready” after refining activities</li>
                <li>Product Backlog refinement is the act of breaking down and further defining Product Backlog items
                    into smaller more precise items. This is an ongoing activity to add details, such as a description,
                    order, and size.</li>
                <li>The Developers who will be doing the work are responsible for the sizing. The Product Owner may
                    influence the Developers by helping them understand and select trade-offs.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a6_2">
            <ul>
                <li>Has a commitment to <b>Sprint Goal</b></li>
                <li>Composed of:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Sprint Goal (“why”)</li>
                        <li>Product Backlog items selected for the Sprint (“what”)</li>
                        <li>Actionable plan for delivering the increment (“how”)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Highly visible, real-time picture of the work to achieve the Sprint Goal</li>
                <li>Created by Developers for Developers</li>
                <li>Updated throughout the Sprint as more is learned</li>
                <li>Should have enough detail for progress inspection in the Daily Scrum. </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a6_3">
            <ul>
                <li>Has a commitment to <b>Definition of Done</b></li>
                <li>Concrete stepping stone toward the Product Goal</li>
                <li>Thoroughly verified, ensuring that all Increments work together</li>
                <li>In order to provide value, the Increment must be usable.</li>
                <li>Multiple Increments may be created within a Sprint and presented at the Sprint Review</li>
                <li>Increment may be delivered to stakeholders prior to the end of the Sprint.</li>
                <li>Sprint Review should never be considered a gate to releasing value.</li>
                <li>Work cannot be considered part of an Increment unless it meets the Definition of Done.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="hidden">
        <div id="a7_1">
            <ul>
                <li>Вescribes a future state of the product - is the long-term objective for the Scrum Team</li>
                <li>Objectives must fulfill (or abandon) one objective before taking on the next</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a7_2">
            <ul>
                <li>Single objective for the Sprint</li>
                <li>Although the Sprint Goal is a commitment by the Developers, it provides flexibility in
                    terms of the exact work needed to achieve it.</li>
                <li>Creates coherence and focus, encouraging the Scrum Team to work together</li>
                <li>Created during the Sprint Planning and added to the Sprint Backlog</li>
                <li>If the work turns out to be different than they expected, Developers collaborate with the
                    Product Owner to negotiate the scope of the Sprint Backlog within the Sprint without affecting
                    the Sprint Goal. </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div id="a7_3">
            <ul>
                <li>Formal description of the state of the Increment when it meets the quality measures required for
                    the product</li>
                <li>The moment a Product Backlog item meets the Definition of Done, an Increment is born</li>
                <li>Creates transparency by providing everyone a shared understanding of what work was completed as
                    part of the Increment</li>
                <li>If a Product Backlog item does not meet the Definition of Done, it cannot be released or even
                    presented at the Sprint Review. Instead, it returns to the Product Backlog for future consideration.</li>
                <li>Definition of Done for an increment is part of the standards of the organization, all Scrum Teams
                    must follow it as a minimum. If it is not an organizational standard, the Scrum Team must create a
                    Definition of Done appropriate for the product.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
